<TITLE> English county players to be tested for skin cancer </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, March 6 (Reuters) - All first class cricketers in England will be tested for skin cancer this season. In an initiative by the Professional Cricketers Association (PCA) about 400 county players will have checks for the disease which is now the UK's most common form of cancer. "Every first class player will get a 20-minute check from a visiting nurse," the PCA's assistant group chief executive Jason Ratcliffe told Reuters on Wednesday. "We are working with the charity Screen4Life and aiming to fit into the county schedules so that we can make sure we are looking after our players properly." No England-based players are thought to have have contracted skin cancer through exposure to the sun during matches, although there have been several causes for concern, added former Warwickshire and Surrey player Ratcliffe. Screen4Life are already offering assistance in a similar initiative with golf's European PGA Tour, testing players and caddies. According to UK-based Screen4Life there are 100,000 cases of skin cancer detected in the UK each year with more people now dying from it here than in Australi
